## Topics Covered

### 1. File System Module (fs)

The `fs` module is a built-in Node.js module used to interact with the file system. It allows reading, writing, updating, and deleting files.

```js
const fs = require("fs");
```

---

### 2. File Operations

#### Write File

Creates a new file or overwrites an existing file.

```js
fs.writeFile("data.txt", "Hello", (err) => {});
```

---

#### Read File

Reads the content of a file.

```js
fs.readFile("data.txt", "utf-8", (err, data) => {});
```

---

#### Append File

Adds new content to an existing file.

```js
fs.appendFile("data.txt", "New Line", (err) => {});
```

---

#### Delete File

Deletes a file from the system.

```js
fs.unlink("data.txt", (err) => {});
```

---

### 3. Asynchronous Behavior in Node.js

Node.js file operations are asynchronous. This means execution does not wait for one task to complete before moving to the next.

#### Incorrect Approach

```js
fs.writeFile(...);
fs.readFile(...);
```

In this case, the read operation may execute before the write operation finishes.

---

#### Correct Approach (Callback Chaining)

```js
fs.writeFile("data.txt", "Hello", (err) => {
    if (!err) {
        fs.readFile("data.txt", "utf-8", (err, data) => {
            console.log(data);
        });
    }
});
```

This ensures that the file is read only after it has been successfully written.

